{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614502"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:45:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16370"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16370"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.05,0,0.62,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114221"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9061"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96221"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7199"},{"type":"tags","id":"7200"},{"type":"tags","id":"7201"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21542"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22146"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114221"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cranial nerves exit the skull through various foramina. Some foramina transmit multiple cranial nerves, making these locations potential sites of multiple nerve compression.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the location where cranial nerves IX, X, and XI exit the skull?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Foramen ovale","Superior orbital fissure","Internal auditory meatus","Jugular foramen","Hypoglossal canal"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ejugular foramen\u003C/strong\u003E is the exit point for three cranial nerves: the glossopharyngeal (CN IX), vagus (CN X), and accessory (CN XI) nerves. This makes it a clinically significant location where pathology can affect multiple cranial nerves simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eforamen ovale\u003C/strong\u003E transmits the mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3), whilst the \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior orbital fissure\u003C/strong\u003E transmits cranial nerves III, IV, V1 and VI. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal auditory meatus\u003C/strong\u003E transmits cranial nerves VII and VIII, and the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglossal canal\u003C/strong\u003E transmits only cranial nerve XII. Lesions affecting the jugular foramen can present with multiple cranial nerve palsies, affecting functions such as swallowing, phonation, and shoulder movement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cranial nerves IX (glossopharyngeal), X (vagus), and XI (accessory) all exit the skull through the jugular foramen.","The jugular foramen is located between the temporal and occipital bones at the base of the skull."],"references":["Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Griessenauer CJ, McGrew B, Matusz P, De Caro R, Loukas M, Tubbs RS. Surgical Approaches to the Jugular Foramen: A Comprehensive Review. J Neurol Surg B Skull Base. 2016 Jun;77(3):260-4. doi: 10.1055/s-0035-1567863. Epub 2015 Nov 16. PMID: 27175322; PMCID: PMC4862834."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96221"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16370"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96221"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T13:46:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T13:46:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9061"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114221"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{